"Abstract Peering and transit agreements allow smaller ISPs to extend their reach into regions where they would otherwise lack infrastructure, and keep traffic on Internet Protocol (IP) networks longer before it reaches a gateway to the pricey PSTN/PSN network, where the call is completed. Such interconnections are vital for smaller ISPs since only by interconnecting can the IP traffic travel furthest and the cost benefit of using the net be maximised. This article by Rohan Kariyawasam looks at packet-switched networks using the transmission control protocol/Internet protocol (TCP/IP) and the interconnection of such networks through peering ."
